ce:section.ce:para:
As a new generation of carbon materials in nanotechnology, carbon quantum dots (CQDs) has attracted substantial attention because of structural availability with several oxygen-containing functional groups (carboxylic, hydroxyl, epoxy) for use in various applications (
                     Rezaei et al., 2016
                     ). The CQDs have numerous merits such as low toxicity, small particle size, high surface area, low costs, chemical stability and susceptibility for additional functionalization (
                     Shen et al., 2012; Wei et al., 2016
                     ). Due to their substantial, abundant and cheap nature, as well as size-dependent optical characteristics, CQDs have been developed with increased and noticeable superiority as new nanocarbon materials in different fields, for example, photocatalysis, compound detecting and analysis, bioimaging/biosensing and electrocatalysis (
                     Hutton et al., 2017; Li et al., 2012a,b; Lim et al., 2015; Shen et al., 2012; Wang et al., 2017a; Wu et al., 2013
                     ). Many applications of CQDs or their functionalized counterparts have been commonly reported in the fields of chemical detection or sensing, particularly for the recognition and capture of some metals including lead and mercury (
                     Wee et al., 2013; Ren et al., 2017; Yan et al., 2014
                     ).

CQDs are generally synthesized by different routes that depend on thermal decomposition of organic compounds including microwave-assisted pyrolysis approach or hydrothermal method, utilizing starch, citric acid, lysine and other sources of carbon (
                     Chen et al., 2017; Wang et al., 2016a
                     ). These approaches and techniques have directed illustrious attentions to enable the utilization of enormous variation of precursors with organic natures to produce CQDs products by offering economical way of preparation with various and appropriate nanoscales (
                     Choi et al., 2017
                     ). In addition, the incorporated characteristics award CQDs with prospective to modify their surface with the aim of improvement in their adsorption capacities for utilization in water treatment (
                     Huang et al., 2019
                     ). The comparison between traditional adsorbents (activated carbon, zeolite, etc.) and modified-CQDs are related to the superior high removal efficiency in adsorption and removal processes of different pollutants from water (
                     Huang et al., 2019
                     ). The typical interaction mechanisms between pollutants (i.e., metal ions or dyes) and CQDs are a combination of physical adsorption, ion-exchange, electrostatic interaction, complexation and H-bonding (
                     Yao et al., 2018
                     ). Therefore, CQDs have been recently implemented in the forms of layered double hydroxide for purification of wastewater containing Cd(II) ions and some anionic dyes (
                     Huang et al., 2019
                     ). However, owing to the high solubility of CQDs, no research has been specifically addressed the subject of free CQDs in water treatment (Rahmanian et al., 2018). To overcome this problem, research considerations have been recently focused on CQDs-based composites for removal of toxic metal ions (
                     Huang et al., 2019
                     ). The modified resultant CQDs can then be optimized with some functional groups in the forms of carboxylated-CQDs, amine-CQDs and thiol-CQDs that are known for their effective binding behaviors with the toxic ions from water (
                     Cayuela et al., 2016; Wang et al., 2015, 2017
                     )

Uranium is one of the supreme vital elements due to its economic importance (
                     Wang et al., 2017b, 2016
                     ). Uranium is used in the development of nuclear energy industry instead of low-carbon power sources (
                     Tan et al., 2015; Gupta et al., 2003). Uranium exists in three radioisotopes (234U, 235U, and 238U), but common of them are 238U isotope (99.27 %) (
                     Camacho et al., 2010
                     ). Nuclear power plants consistently require U assets; hence, 4.5 billion tons of all out U in sea water can be recuperated for nuclear power usage (
                     Choi et al., 2003
                     ). In 2011, Japan suffered from the radioactive isotopes that contaminated water after Fukushima Daiichi nuclear accident. The radioactive uranium compounds as pollutants can cause cancer and damage biological system of the human body (
                     Zhao et al., 2012
                     ). According to WHO, the maximum concentration of U(VI) ions must not exceed 15 μg L−1 in drinking water (
                     World Health Organization, 1993
                     ). As a result, the extraction of U(VI) from water is very important for environmental and human health (
                     Farasati et al., 2016
                     ). The adsorption technique is considered the most proficient for removing metal ions which is often applied due to its simplicity, high effectiveness process, and low costs (
                     Farasati et al., 2016; Mahmoud and Fekry, 2018; Wu et al., 2019; Mahmoud et al., 2016; Wang et al., 2009; Mahmoud et al., 2018
                     ). However, limited researches have been focused on sorption performance of either free CQDs or modified resultant CQDs as efficient nanoadsorbents in the field of uranium ions removal from wastewater treatment. As an example, the modification of CQDs by SBA-NH2 was synthesized for removal U(VI) from wastewater, which confirmed high adsorption effectiveness and provided a suitable route to monitor the adsorption operation (
                     Wang et al., 2017b
                     ).

CQDs were prepared from starch as a cheap source via one-step pyrolysis using microwave irradiation process (
                        Das et al., 2018; Choi et al., 2017
                        ). Firstly, 6 g of starch was dissolved in 40 mL of deionized water. After that, the beaker was heated inside a microwave oven at 700 W for 10 min. During this time, the solution was converted into brown color indicating the formation of CQDs. The product material was cooled and 50 mL of deionized water was then added. This mixture was sonicated for 30 min to finally obtain the CQDs as suspension in aqueous solution.

The microwave irradiation has assisted and accomplished the pyrolysis of starch-water system in 10 min without any chemical reagents. However, the continued microwave treatment of starch more than 10 min was found to produce the black precipitate due to formation of carbon. The structural features of CQDs, PAFP and CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent have been examined by FT-IR. The FT-IR spectrum of CQDs (Fig. 1
                           ) showed the characteristic peaks of OH (3320 cm−1), CH (2918 cm−1), COOH (1704 cm−1), CC (1637 cm−1), CH2 bending (1411 cm−1) and COC (1013 cm−1). Two other peaks (572 and 526 cm−1) were assigned to CH symmetric bending vibrations ( 
                           Yu et al., 2012; Hu et al., 2019; Li et al., 2012a,b; Gong et al., 2014; Miao et al., 2016; Basu et al., 2015
                           ). The FT-IR spectrum of PAFP is also given in Fig. 1 in which a broad band at 3376 cm−1 is due to (OH/NH) vibration of ArCOOH and Ar-NH2, respectively, and intramolecular H-bonding. The peak appeared at 1212 cm−1 is referring to (CN) stretching vibration of Ar-NH2. The peak at 2890 cm−1 may be assigned to (CH2-) linkage in the PAFP. The weak band at 3027 cm−1 is ascribed to the (CH) vibration of methylene group (
                           Al Hamouz, 2016; Singru et al., 2010; Atia et al., 2005
                           ). The strong band at 1705 cm-1 may be related to (CO) of non-ionic (COOH) (
                           Ogura et al., 1999
                           ). The sharp peak at 1622 cm-1 may refer to (CC) (
                           Al Hamouz, 2016
                           ). The two peaks at 1174 and 1017 cm-1 are related to (CH) stretching vibration of methylene group. The FT-IR of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is also shown in Fig. 1. The specific band at 3413 cm-1 was attributed to (-NH/OH) from the polymer and CQDs. The weak band at 3032 cm-1 is due to the (CH) vibration in methylene group from the polymer matrix. The two peaks at 2931 and 2887 cm-1 are due to CH and CH2, respectively. The two peaks at 1710 and 1208 cm-1 are due to (CO) and (-C-O-), respectively, indicating that may be the formation an ester bond linkage between COOH of PAFP and OH of CQDs. In addition, the other peaks at 1623, 1516, 1171 and 1069 cm−1 were turned sharper to confirm that the CQDs particles were successfully incubated within the surface of polymer for formation of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent.

To confirm the size of synthesized CQDs and CQDs@PAFP, TEM was investigated. Fig. 3
                           a and b show the image of CQDs and CQDs@PAFP, respectively. The CQDs are homogenous, spherical and monodispersed, with particle size about 4−5 nm. CQDs@PAFP image indicates that nanosheets in the view with doping of CQDs to form layers. The average particle size of CQDs@PAFP was 57.88 nm, to confirm the assignment of CQDs@PAFP as a nanobiosorbent. The UV–vis spectrum (Fig. 3c) also displays the characterized absorption peak of CQDs at 280 nm due to the π-π* transition (
                           Long et al., 2012
                           ). The PL of CQDs depends on the nature of excitation wavelength (
                           Liu et al., 2011
                           ). The maximum emission of CQDs was detected at 526 nm throughout the excitation wavelength (390 nm).

The thermogram of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is represented in Fig. 5b. The degradation of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is based on three different stages. The first stage (35.66 to 218.64 °C)(35.66–218.64 °C) with the weight loss = 4.828 % is due to water molecules loss from the surface of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent. The second stage (218.64–464.02 °C and loss = 35.08 %) may be related to partial thermal degradation of PAFP of CQDs from the surface of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent (
                           Tyagi et al., 2016
                           ). Finally, the third stage (464.02 - 599.94 °C and loss = 53.47 %) was assigned to the complete thermal degradation of CQDs and PAFP.

The increasing of U(VI) removal with pH increase, can be elucidated with respect to the point of zero charge (pHPZC) of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent and U(VI) speciation in solution. The point of zero charge of sorbent (pHPZC) occur when the charge of CQDs@PAFP surface is zero. The pHPZC of CQDs@PAFP was at pH 4.0 (Fig. 7
                        ). At pH < pHPZC, the surface charge of CQDs@PAFP is positive and U(VI) species are positively charged. Thus, the removal of U(VI) is lower at pH < pHPZC due to the high concentration of H+ in solution that competing with the (UO2
                        2+). At pH > pHPZC, the surface charge of CQDs@PAFP is negative and U(VI) species are positively charged (till pH < 7.0). This situation enhanced the attraction between CQDs@PAFP and (UO2
                        2+), which ultimately confirm the increased removal of U(VI). In other hand, the species of U(VI) above pH 7.0 are existing as negatively charged and the surface charge of CQDs@PAFP is negative, in which the removal of U(VI) will be decreased again. The maximum removal of U(VI) by CQDs@PAFP was achieved at pH 5.0 (
                        Mahmoud et al., 2017
                        ).

The mass content of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is a significant parameter to affect the adsorption capacities of U(VI) owning to the limited active sites and effective areas of CQDs@PAFP, which should be taken into deliberate during the removal process. This study has been accomplished by using CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent dosages in the range 1.0–40.0 ± 0.1 mg at pH 5.0 and 30 s microwave heating and the data are illustrated in Fig. 6b. One can noticeably appreciate that the percentage extraction of U(VI) augmented rapidly with the rise in CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent mass content (
                        Basu et al., 2015
                        ). At 1 mg of nanobiosorbent content, the removal of U(VI) was obtained as 30.2, 34.3 and 36.5 % for 30, 60 and 90 mg L−1, respectively. Thus, the number of active groups on CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is less compared to the number of persevering U(VI) ions. Upon using 10 mg, the concentration of U(VI) is less compared to the number of active sites, and thereby resulting in a slow increase in percentage removal of U(VI). The highest percentage values were 97.1 % (30 mg L−1), 98.6 % (60 mg L−1) and 99.7 % (90 mg L−1), respectively, indicating excellent binding between U(VI) with nitrogen and oxygen-containing CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent.

The adsorption process of U(VI) onto CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent was scrutinized utilizing the pseudo-first-order, pseudo-second-order, and intraparticle diffusion kinetic models (Table 3
                        ). The qe(cal) from pseudo-first-order equation is poor (Table 3). This suggests that the adsorption of U(VI) onto CQDs@PAFP didn’t obey this model. The adsorption experimental data of U(VI) onto CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent was fitted to pseudo-second order according to the R2 values for the three investigated concentrations of U(VI). In addition, there was only a little alteration between qe(exp) and qe(cal) to confirm the applicability of pseudo-second order model (
                        Mahmoud et al., 2020b
                        ). The qe(cal) of U(VI) values on CQDs@PAFP were 29.93, 61.19 and 92.16 mg g−1 for 30, 60 and 90 mg L-1, respectively indicating that the CQDs@PAFP exhibited superior performance on U(VI) removal. The pseudo-second order was found more suitable than pseudo-first order, indicating that chemical adsorption could be listed and correlated as the rate-determining step of U(VI) onto CQD@PAFP (Ho and Mckay, 2000; Tang et al., 2020, Park et al., 2020; Li et al., 2012a, b).The R2 values of pseudo-second order were 0.9979, 0.9980 and 0.9978 upon using 30, 60 and 90 mg L-1, respectively. In intraparticle diffusion, Kid values were 24.21, 44.30 and 65.62 mg g-1 min-1/5 for 30, 60 and 90 mg L-1, respectively. The values of C were 12.81, 29.64 and 45.47 mg g-1 for 30, 60 and 90 mg L-1, respectively (not passing through the origin), indicating that the diffusion and degree layer control was not only the rate controlling step (
                        Mahmoud and Fekry, 2018
                        ). Finally, the R2 values of Elovich model were 0.9969, 0.9917 and 0.9962 by 30, 60 and 90 mg L-1, respectively.

The thermodynamic parameters (ΔGo, ΔHo and ΔSo) were measured at different temperatures 293, 309, 333 and 343. Although there are several papers reported in the literature using these relationships as the equilibrium constant such as KC= (Co-Ce)/(Co) or KD= qe/Ce for obtaining the thermodynamic parameters, the thermodynamic parameters obtained by these KC or KD are incorrect as previously reported (
                        Lima et al., 2019; Anastopoulos et al., 2019; Liu, 2009
                        ). The thermodynamic parameters can be estimated from the best isotherm adsorption. The values of Freundlich constant were 3.35 (at 293 K), 4.38 (at 309 K), 6.41 (at 333 K) and 7.47 (at 343 K) (mg g−1)(L mg−1)1/n. The calculated Ke from Eq.(13), ΔGo from Eq. (14) and plotted relation between lnKe and 1/T. The calculated parameters from slope and intercept are listed in the Table 6
                        . The negative ΔGo and positive ΔHo values of U(VI) onto CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent refer that the reactions were spontaneous and endothermic process for the three investigated concentrations. The ΔGo values decreased with temperature increasing, indicating that adsorption capacities of U(VI) on CQDs@PAFP were increased. At different temperatures, the calculated ΔGo values were -19.77, -21.54, -24.27 and -25.44 KJ. mol−1. This phenomenon may be correlated to the alteration of complexation constant of U(VI) onto CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent surface at various T. The positive value of ΔSo may be due to changed structure of U(VI) loaded on CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent during the sorption process, that increasing more disorder between solid and solution (
                        Mahmoud et al., 2019a
                        ).

During adsorption process, the impact of competing ions factor was applied owing to the presence of various existing ions in real water matrices (
                        Shreadah et al., 2019; Mahmoud et al., 2019b
                        ). The extraction of U(VI) by CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is presented in Fig. 6d in the presence of interfering (KCl, NH4Cl, NaCl, CaCl2 and MgSO4) and without interference. In general, all percentages of U(VI) extraction were decreased with the existence of interference ions. The percentages of U(VI) extraction was deceased to 82.9 %, 91.4 % and 94.2 % using 30, 60 and 90 mg L−1, respectively, in presence of NaCl. The percentage of U(VI) was slightly decreased in presence of 30 mg L−1 of MgSO4 (94.1 %), but slightly increased by 60 mg L-1 (97.1 %) and 90 mg L-1 (98.1 %). This result can be correlated to the selectivity of U(VI) for binding with the active functional groups on the surface of CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent compared to other ions. The ANOVA test confirmed that the values of U(VI) percentage removal are not significantly different (p-value > 0.05).

The reusability of different sorbents such as CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent is a significant factor with respect to the economical factor according to the repeated application cycles. In this study, the regeneration of the CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent was investigated by using HCl as the recycling reagent (
                        Mahmoud and Fekry, 2018
                        ). The removal efficiency values of U(VI) ions by CQDs@PAFP nanobiosorbent were characterized to correspond to 97.1 %, 95.6 %, 93.8 % and 89.5 % for the first, second, third and fourth cycles, respectively. After the fifth cycles, the efficiency of U(VI) removal was identified as 85.2 %. The outlined results refer that the regenerated CQDs@PAFP is an excellent reusable nanobiosorbent and can be efficiently employed for U(VI) recovery from different water matrices.
